	​

])

🔧 Implementation (C++)
int knapsack(int W, vector<int>& wt, vector<int>& val, int n) {
    vector<vector<int>> dp(n+1, vector<int>(W+1, 0));

    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
        for (int w = 0; w <= W; w++) {
            if (wt[i-1] <= w) {
                dp[i][w] = max(dp[i-1][w],
                               val[i-1] + dp[i-1][w - wt[i-1]]);
            } else {
                dp[i][w] = dp[i-1][w];
            }
        }
    }

    return dp[n][W];
}
🧠 Viva Line:

“Unlike fractional knapsack, 0/1 knapsack requires DP because items cannot be split, and greedy may miss the optimal combination.”

🔸 2. Multi-Stage Delivery Cost Optimization
📦 Problem

A delivery route has multiple stages (warehouse → hub → customer).

👉 Goal:
Minimize total cost across all stages

🧠 Idea:

Break into stages and store minimum cost to reach each stage.

🔧 Implementation
int multiStageGraph(int stages, vector<vector<int>>& cost) {
    int n = cost.size();
    vector<int> dp(n, INT_MAX);

    dp[n-1] = 0; // last node

    for (int i = n-2; i >= 0; i--) {
        for (int j = i+1; j < n; j++) {
            if (cost[i][j] != INT_MAX) {
                dp[i] = min(dp[i], cost[i][j] + dp[j]);
            }
        }
    }

    return dp[0];
}
🧠 Viva Line:

“This models multi-stop delivery planning where each stage decision depends on future costs.”

🔸 3. Floyd-Warshall (All-Pairs Shortest Path)
📦 Problem

Find shortest path between every pair of locations

👉 Useful for:

Precomputing routes
Fast lookup during delivery
🧠 DP Recurrence

dist[i][j]=min(dist[i][j], dist[i][k]+dist[k][j])

🔧 Implementation
void floydWarshall(vector<vector<int>>& dist, int n) {
    for (int k = 0; k < n; k++) {
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j < n; j++) {
                if (dist[i][k] != INT_MAX && dist[k][j] != INT_MAX) {
                    dist[i][j] = min(dist[i][j],
                                     dist[i][k] + dist[k][j]);
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
🧠 Viva Line:

“Floyd-Warshall uses dynamic programming to compute shortest paths between all pairs, enabling constant-time route lookup.”
